>
  <p>One of the first things I care about with a system like OpenClaw is safety.</p>

  <p>
    Not in the abstract “AI safety” sense only, but in the practical everyday sense: what should this assistant be
    allowed to do, what should it avoid doing, and how do I keep it useful without letting it become reckless or
    intrusive?
  </p>

  <h2>What matters to me</h2>

  <p>If an assistant is going to live near my real workflow, it has to understand boundaries.</p>

  <p>That means things like:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>not treating access as permission to do everything</li>
    <li>being cautious with messages, emails, and anything external-facing</li>
    <li>keeping personal context private</li>
    <li>asking before making destructive or irreversible changes</li>
    <li>avoiding noisy behavior that creates more friction than value</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For me, safety is not separate from usability. A system that is technically powerful but socially clumsy is not actually safe in daily life.</p>

  <h2>The trust test</h2>

  <p>The real test is whether I feel comfortable letting it stay close to ongoing work.</p>

  <p>That trust depends less on big promises and more on repeated small behavior:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>does it understand when to ask first?</li>
    <li>does it avoid over-sharing?</li>
    <li>does it keep track of context without becoming invasive?</li>
    <li>does it behave consistently?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>If the answer to those questions starts drifting, the system stops feeling like an assistant and starts feeling like a risk.</p>
